{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b39fe8a5-f139-4e8b-8cff-d09e02f3ed34","content":"Since you have root and need **native** call stacks, Linux `perf` is the best tool — `dotnet-trace` (EventPipe) only captures managed frames.\n\n### Recommended approach\n\n**1. Enable managed-frame resolution** (set before launching your service):\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_PerfMapEnabled=1          # emits /tmp/perf-<pid>.map\nexport DOTNET_EnableWriteXorExecute=0   # allows perf to read JIT'd code\n```\n\n**2. Record a CPU profile** (with call-graph unwinding):\n\n```bash\n# DWARF unwinding gives the best native+managed stacks\nperf record -g --call-graph dwarf -p <PID> -- sleep 30\n```\n\n**3. Visualize as a flamegraph:**\n\n```bash\n# Using Brendan Gregg's FlameGraph scripts\nperf script | stackcollapse-perf.pl | flamegraph.pl > cpu.svg\n```\n\n### Why `perf` over `dotnet-trace`?\n\n| | `perf` | `dotnet-trace` |\n|---|---|---|\n| Native frames | ✅ full kernel + userspace | ❌ managed only |\n| Root required | yes | no |\n| Overhead | very low (sampling) | low |\n| Managed symbols | via PerfMap | built-in |\n\n### Tips\n- If the service is already running without `PerfMapEnabled`, you can trigger map generation by sending `SIGUSR2` — .NET 10 supports on-demand perf map emission.\n- Use `--call-graph dwarf` (not `fp`) because .NET JIT doesn't preserve frame pointers by default.\n- For mixed managed+native flamegraphs, install the `dotnet-symbol` tool to pull framework symbols: `dotnet tool install -g dotnet-symbol`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"feea945e-9c00-4db0-a49a-3660476eebc5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting performance traces with native call stacks on a .NET 10 application running on Linux. This is a diagnostics/performance question, not a code change request. Let me provide a concise, expert answer.\n\nKey points:\n- .NET 10 on Linux with root access\n- High CPU, suspect native code\n- Wants rich trace with native call stacks\n\nThe best approach for this scenario is using `dotnet-trace` with the `perf` profile or, even better, using Linux `perf` directly since they have root access and need native call stacks. `dotnet-trace` by default uses EventPipe which doesn't capture native frames well. For native call stacks, `perf` is the gold standard on Linux.\n \nFor native call stacks, `perf record` with the `-g` flag is the way to go—it captures the full call graph. .NET provides perf map support so managed frames get resolved properly in the output, making `perf` combined with .NET's perf maps the most effective combination here.\n\nTo set this up on .NET 10, I'd enable perf maps through environment variables, then use `perf record` to collect traces with call graphs, and finally convert the output to a readable format like speedscope or flamegraph. While `dotnet-trace` exists as an alternative, it's limited to managed events and won't capture native frames, so for comprehensive profiling with root access, `perf` is definitely the better choice.","outputTokens":1180,"requestId":"AC0F:13323C:1414C0A:166CE5F:6A066E80"},"id":"841abc13-4b71-4398-b809-1b78cbc5d7b7","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:53:48.775Z","parentId":"0703eaa2-3f99-4a1c-ad40-4496afa54b11"}
